build: fix Meson warnings

WARNING: You should add the boolean check kwarg to the run_command call.
         It currently defaults to false,
         but it will default to true in future releases of meson.
         See also: https://github.com/mesonbuild/meson/issues/9300

arena: add workaround for unimplemented mincore() on WSL 1

Windows Subsystem for Linux v1 does not support mincore(), but the
available Linux distributions on WSL use unmodified libc packages, which
export mincore().

In that case, mincore() returns ENOSYS.

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/release-notes

arena: extract page_mapped_msync()

Signed-off-by: László Várady <laszlo.varady@protonmail.com>

sandbox: try using "debugserver" on macOS when fallback is enabled

debugserver is the official LLVM-based debug server on macOS.
In case the fallback flag is enabled, debugserver will be preferred over
lldb-server.

In order to be backward compatible, this is done only then the fallback
flag is set.

boxfort: add BXF_DBG_FALLBACK debug flag

The flag can be used to indicate that when the specified debugger can not
be found, the sandboxed process should be suspended instead.
exe: move trampoline fixup to a separate unit

exe-elf: word-align trampoline code

Thumb is a halfword-aligned instruction set encoding, but our trampoline
code uses a PC-relative jump, which needs to be positioned on a word
aligned address.
exe-elf: detect ARM Thumb-mode main() function, patch accordingly

exe-elf: fix main's address when main() is an ARM Thumb function

https://developer.arm.com/documentation/dui0471/m/interworking-arm-and-thumb/pointers-to-functions-in-thumb-state

Pointers to Thumb functions have their least significant bit set to
ensure that interworking works correctly.

That bit is just an indicator, we need to get rid of it before patching
the function with our trampoline.
exe-elf: add possibility to inject a prelude code into main()

exe-elf: add possibility to fixup trampoline code

bxfi_exe_trampoline_fixup() can be used to make small modifications on the
trampoline code or on the function being patched.

trampoline-arm: add trampoline for patching a Thumb function

Thumb is an ARM instruction set encoding, it uses 16-bit instructions
instead of 32.

When patching such a function, we should use a Thumb-encoded trampoline.

trampoline-arm: support jumping to Thumb function from ARM mode

BX exchanges the instruction set if necessary.

build: use uppercase BXF_ARCH_* macros

This fixes the BXF_ARCH_ARM and BXF_ARCH_ARM64 macros as well.
ci: add native arm builds

sandbox,posix: fallback to /proc/self/fd

Some container environments do not create the /dev/fd symlink.

exe-mach-o: do not acquire X and W mprotection at the same time

This is not allowed on Apple silicon.

exe-elf: remove dead code
exe: fix include guard

exe: clear CPU instruction cache after patching main

BoxFort workers replace their own main function by injecting asm
instructions into their original main().

CPU cache lines have to be flushed after modifying executable memory in
order to obtain deterministic behavior.

This fixes sandboxing on aarch64, for example: Snaipe/Criterion#312

Note: Currently, bxfi_exe_clear_cache() is not implemented for Windows.

build: specify shell for cram tests

This is an attempt to fix cram tests in non-POSIX-compliant environment.

exe-mach-o: bypass max_protection using mach_vm_protect(VM_PROT_COPY)

max_prot disallows injecting the BoxFort trampoline into main()'s location.

This commit replaces the mprotect() call with vm_protect(VM_PROT_COPY),
which gets (COW) a writable page.

timeout-posix: fix race condition

The posix timeout code was racy -- if a timeout was created, and
cancelled before the watchdog had any chance to run (because the worker
would exit too quickly, or because the thread would not be scheduled
quickly enough). This, in turn, made the watchdog wait forever for the
timeout queue to be nonempty.

This fixes the race by preventing the watchdog from ever waiting for the
queue to fill up -- it's actually not possible for the queue to be
empty during initialization, because the watchdog thread will be made to
wait for the initialization lock to be released. This means that the
only time where the queue is empty is when the watchdog has been
started, but the worker already exited/the timeout was cancelled.

In addition, this fix simplifies slightly the way that the watchdog is
collected -- we no longer try to join the thread, but we make it
detached from the get go.

This addresses Snaipe/Criterion#345.

Search for cram as cram3

In Debian Bullseye and later cram is called cram3 (as that is the python3
version)
